SIMPLE: obstinacy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obstinacy
<hw>Ob"sti*na*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Obstinate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fixedness in will,
opinion, or resolution that can not be shaken at all, or only with great
difficulty; firm and usually unreasonable adherence to an opinion,
purpose, or system; unyielding disposition; stubbornness; pertinacity;
persistency; contumacy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You do not well in <qex>obstinacy</qex>⟦br⟧
To cavil in the course of this contract.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To shelter their ignorance, or <qex>obstinacy</qex>, under the
obscurity of their terms.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being difficult to remedy,
relieve, or subdue; <as>as, the <ex>obstinacy</ex> of a disease or
evil</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Pertinacity; firmness; resoluteness;
inflexibility; persistency; stubbornness; perverseness; contumacy.</syn>
<usage> -- <er>Obstinacy</er>, <er>Pertinacity</er>.
<xex>Pertinacity</xex> denotes great firmness in holding to a thing,
aim, etc. <xex>Obstinacy</xex> is great firmness in holding out against
persuasion, attack, etc. The former consists in adherence, the latter in
resistance. An opinion is advocated with pertinacity or defended with
<xex>obstinacy</xex>. <xex>Pertinacity</xex> is often used in a good
sense; <xex>obstinacy</xex> generally in a bad one. ⟦ldquo⟧In this reply
was included a very gross mistake, and if with <xex>pertinacity</xex>
maintained, a capital error.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir T. Browne.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Every
degree of <xex>obstinacy</xex> in youth is one step to rebellion.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>South.</au></usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obstinate</ent>⟦br⟧
